1
00:00:00,531 --> 00:00:04,252
[SPEAKER_12]: for decades, decades, decades, decades.

2
00:00:05,292 --> 00:00:21,396
[SPEAKER_12]: Even before finishing her doctorate, she was conducting independent research at the University of Chicago's Marine Biological Laboratory, studying how cells respond to ultraviolet light, hormones, and experimental drugs.

3
00:00:22,417 --> 00:00:27,458
[SPEAKER_12]: These were early steps towards understanding melanoma at the cellular level.

4
00:00:29,530 --> 00:00:37,154
[SPEAKER_12]: After graduation, she joined Harlem Hospital Cancer Research Foundation, working alongside Dr. Jane C. Wright.

5
00:00:38,475 --> 00:00:50,502
[SPEAKER_12]: There, Jewel mastered human tissue culture, growing real cancer cells from patient biopsies so drugs could be tested before reaching human bodies.

6
00:00:52,523 --> 00:00:55,765
[SPEAKER_12]: It changed cancer treatment forever.

7
00:00:57,408 --> 00:01:02,210
[SPEAKER_12]: It changed cancer treatment forever.

8
00:01:03,871 --> 00:01:08,613
[SPEAKER_12]: It changed cancer treatment forever.

9
00:01:11,614 --> 00:01:18,557
[SPEAKER_12]: At just 28, Jewel found her own tissue culture lab at the University of Illinois College of Medicine.

10
00:01:19,930 --> 00:01:25,596
[SPEAKER_12]: a black woman leading independent cancer research in the 1950s.

11
00:01:26,016 --> 00:01:38,869
[SPEAKER_12]: While the funding committees doubted her competence and colleagues questioned her data and journals fought to minimize her authorship, Jewel, she persisted anyway.

12
00:01:40,693 --> 00:01:55,841
[SPEAKER_12]: Her melanoma research revealed how melanin protects cells from UV damage and how cancer cells fundamentally differ from healthy ones, finding that became cornerstones of modern skin cancer science.

13
00:01:57,782 --> 00:02:03,565
[SPEAKER_12]: That became cornerstones of modern skin cancer science.

14
00:02:04,625 --> 00:02:06,666
[SPEAKER_12]: Then came the work that saved lives.

15
00:02:07,666 --> 00:02:18,471
[SPEAKER_12]: In the early 1960s, Juul helped demonstrate the power of methotrexate against skin cancer, lung cancer, and childhood leukemia.

16
00:02:19,651 --> 00:02:25,834
[SPEAKER_12]: Research that helped establish one of the most important chemotherapy drugs in medical history.

17
00:02:27,395 --> 00:02:33,217
[SPEAKER_12]: One of the most important chemotherapy medical drugs in history.

18
00:02:34,760 --> 00:02:37,303
[SPEAKER_12]: a drug still used today and saving lives.

19
00:02:38,124 --> 00:02:41,328
[SPEAKER_12]: But Jewel never forgot the hallway at NYU.

20
00:02:43,150 --> 00:02:48,797
[SPEAKER_12]: She understood that brilliance means nothing if access is denied.

21
00:02:50,492 --> 00:02:53,713
[SPEAKER_12]: So she turned her attention to opening doors.

22
00:02:54,734 --> 00:03:09,520
[SPEAKER_12]: She became a college dean, then earned a second deanship, and in 1981, she broke yet another barrier as the first African American woman president of California State University, Fullerton.

23
00:03:11,751 --> 00:03:25,035
[SPEAKER_12]: There she built scholarships, tutoring programs, and research opportunities for students who had been told, just as she once was, that they did not belong in science.

24
00:03:26,615 --> 00:03:31,557
[SPEAKER_12]: When she retired, she kept mentoring, kept advising, and kept lifting.

25
00:03:34,988 --> 00:03:43,492
[SPEAKER_12]: When Dr. Jewel Plummer Cobb died in 2017 at the age of 92, she left behind more than discoveries.

26
00:03:44,493 --> 00:03:57,299
[SPEAKER_12]: She left behind lives saved, institutions transformed, and generations of scientists who never had to stand alone in a hallway and demand to be seen.

27
00:03:59,125 --> 00:04:02,988
[SPEAKER_12]: She was denied entry because of the color of her skin.

28
00:04:04,249 --> 00:04:05,450
[SPEAKER_12]: She showed up anyway.

29
00:04:07,052 --> 00:04:09,574
[SPEAKER_12]: She showed up anyway.

30
00:04:10,715 --> 00:04:15,279
[SPEAKER_12]: And by refusing to accept a closed door, she changed science.

31
00:04:16,500 --> 00:04:20,083
[SPEAKER_12]: And who gets to belong in it forever?

32
00:04:39,318 --> 00:04:39,718
[SPEAKER_06]: Good morning.

33
00:04:39,738 --> 00:04:46,841
[SPEAKER_06]: It seems the spirit of the 60s has returned in every way.

34
00:04:50,303 --> 00:05:08,671
[SPEAKER_06]: Remembering John Lewis, on July 23rd, 2020, Mr. Ray Sean Ray of the renowned Brookings Institute shared this reflection on the late US Congressman

35
00:05:10,102 --> 00:05:21,024
[SPEAKER_06]: John Lewis, titled, Five Things John Lewis Taught Us About Getting In Good Trouble.

36
00:05:23,285 --> 00:05:24,585
[SPEAKER_06]: Indeed, yes, indeed.

37
00:05:26,965 --> 00:05:36,147
[SPEAKER_06]: Get in good trouble, necessary trouble, and redeem the soul of America.

38
00:05:38,722 --> 00:05:53,768
[SPEAKER_06]: John Lewis made this statement on the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma, Alabama on March 1st, 2020 commemorating the tragic events of Bloody Sunday.

39
00:05:56,729 --> 00:06:04,392
[SPEAKER_06]: Bloody Sunday occurred on March 7th, 1965 as peaceful protesters were beaten by law enforcement

40
00:06:05,350 --> 00:06:11,173
[SPEAKER_06]: something we're too familiar with these days, for crossing the bridge.

41
00:06:12,374 --> 00:06:18,677
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis and others, like Amelia Boynton Robinson, were beaten so badly they were hospitalized.

42
00:06:20,398 --> 00:06:22,359
[SPEAKER_06]: The context behind the march is significant.

43
00:06:23,459 --> 00:06:28,722
[SPEAKER_06]: The 600-person civil rights march was actually about police brutality.

44
00:06:30,764 --> 00:06:41,889
[SPEAKER_06]: Jimmy Lee Jackson, a 26-year-old church deacon, was killed by James Barnard Fowler, a state trooper in Alabama.

45
00:06:43,870 --> 00:06:54,095
[SPEAKER_06]: This march also occurred a year and a half after the infamous March on Washington, highlighting that little had changed in the lives of black people in America.

46
00:06:57,201 --> 00:07:05,444
[SPEAKER_06]: Bloody Sunday was highlighted in Ava DuVernay's Oscar-nominated best picture film, Selma.

47
00:07:09,406 --> 00:07:13,567
[SPEAKER_06]: Bloody Sunday is often noted as a pinnacle of Lewis' life.

48
00:07:15,508 --> 00:07:18,869
[SPEAKER_06]: Number one, vote always.

49
00:07:20,330 --> 00:07:21,070
[SPEAKER_06]: Your vote matters.

50
00:07:21,750 --> 00:07:26,032
[SPEAKER_06]: If it didn't, why would some people keep trying to take it away from us?

51
00:07:30,257 --> 00:07:31,938
[SPEAKER_06]: Hashtag good trouble.

52
00:07:32,419 --> 00:07:34,420
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis sent this tweet on July 3rd, 2018.

53
00:07:35,061 --> 00:07:42,787
[SPEAKER_06]: It highlights his work, equitable voting, his life's work.

54
00:07:45,369 --> 00:07:50,873
[SPEAKER_06]: One major part of the Civil Rights Movement was black people gaining the right to vote.

55
00:07:52,254 --> 00:07:54,316
[SPEAKER_06]: This finally occurred with the Voting Rights Act of 1965.

56
00:07:57,931 --> 00:08:16,237
[SPEAKER_06]: But the Shelby versus Holder Supreme Court decision in 2013 essentially gutted the Voting Rights Act and paved the way for widespread voter suppression and gerrymandering, which we know they hope to do this year as well.

57
00:08:18,442 --> 00:08:20,103
[SPEAKER_06]: Similar forces, of course.

58
00:08:21,103 --> 00:08:33,109
[SPEAKER_06]: This is why it is imperative for Congress to act swiftly to pass the John Lewis Voter Rights Advancement Act to ensure equitable access to the polls.

59
00:08:34,889 --> 00:08:43,013
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis was an original freedom fighter, participated in many sit-ins, and was arrested dozens of times for people to have the right to vote.

60
00:08:45,005 --> 00:08:51,989
[SPEAKER_06]: He said, some of us gave a little blood for the right to participate in the democratic process.

61
00:08:55,351 --> 00:08:56,191
[SPEAKER_06]: Some gave their lives.

62
00:08:58,773 --> 00:09:07,898
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, Congress must honor Lewis's legacy and ensure an equitable participation in the democratic process.

63
00:09:08,899 --> 00:09:11,700
[SPEAKER_06]: As Lewis noted, the vote is precious.

64
00:09:12,721 --> 00:09:14,102
[SPEAKER_06]: It is almost sacred.

65
00:09:15,140 --> 00:09:19,162
[SPEAKER_06]: It is the most powerful nonviolent tool we have in a democracy.

66
00:09:20,763 --> 00:09:25,326
[SPEAKER_06]: Number two, you're never too young to make a difference.

67
00:09:26,787 --> 00:09:36,272
[SPEAKER_06]: As a founder and leader of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee, aka SNCC, Lewis was the youngest person to speak at the march on Washington.

68
00:09:36,532 --> 00:09:37,553
[SPEAKER_06]: He was 23 years old.

69
00:09:39,634 --> 00:09:42,796
[SPEAKER_06]: Elder civil rights leaders aimed to taper his words

70
00:09:44,216 --> 00:09:52,140
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis was critical of the Kennedy administration and the slowness by which broad scale legislation change was occurring at the federal level.

71
00:09:53,841 --> 00:10:00,244
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis also critiqued civil rights legislation for not addressing police brutality against black people.

72
00:10:01,264 --> 00:10:10,009
[SPEAKER_06]: Imagine how this moment in the movement for black lives may be different had elder civil rights leaders listened to John Lewis.

73
00:10:12,333 --> 00:10:20,075
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis stated, I want to see young people in America feel the spirit of the 1960s and find a way to get in the way.

74
00:10:22,776 --> 00:10:29,918
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis stated, I want to see, pardon me, to find a way to get into trouble, good trouble, necessary trouble.

75
00:10:31,559 --> 00:10:37,681
[SPEAKER_06]: Young people can and should push for transformative change and hold us accountable to it.

76
00:10:40,422 --> 00:10:40,862
[SPEAKER_06]: Number three.

77
00:10:42,145 --> 00:10:44,447
[SPEAKER_06]: speak truth to power.

78
00:10:45,788 --> 00:10:46,309
[SPEAKER_06]: Speak up.

79
00:10:47,850 --> 00:10:48,410
[SPEAKER_06]: Speak out.

80
00:10:49,691 --> 00:10:52,374
[SPEAKER_06]: Get in the way, said Lewis.

81
00:10:53,755 --> 00:10:56,557
[SPEAKER_06]: He taught us the importance of speaking up and speaking out.

82
00:10:57,198 --> 00:11:03,263
[SPEAKER_06]: We have to be willing to speak up about injustice always, no matter what the costs.

83
00:11:06,502 --> 00:11:16,266
[SPEAKER_06]: My grandfather who served in two wars earning a purple heart and a bronze star taught me from birth that silence, my silence, is my acceptance.

84
00:11:17,646 --> 00:11:23,249
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis stated, when you see something that is not right, not fair, not just, you have to speak up.

85
00:11:24,829 --> 00:11:25,870
[SPEAKER_06]: You have to say something.

86
00:11:26,070 --> 00:11:27,650
[SPEAKER_06]: You have to do something.

87
00:11:28,131 --> 00:11:30,652
[SPEAKER_06]: This motto should apply in all aspects of our lives.

88
00:11:33,453 --> 00:11:34,073
[SPEAKER_06]: Feel that one.

89
00:11:37,838 --> 00:11:41,039
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis epitomizes it and encourages us not to be silent.

90
00:11:41,339 --> 00:11:46,221
[SPEAKER_06]: After reading about his life, you know, I feel like I'm not doing enough.

91
00:11:50,182 --> 00:11:53,784
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis epitomizes it and encourages us to not be silent.

92
00:11:54,424 --> 00:11:59,786
[SPEAKER_06]: He was adamant about supporting free speech, but he was also adamant about condemning hate speech.

93
00:12:01,606 --> 00:12:02,847
[SPEAKER_06]: I believe in freedom of speech.

94
00:12:04,275 --> 00:12:11,482
[SPEAKER_06]: But I also believe that we have an obligation to condemn speech that is racist, bigoted, anti-Semitic, or hateful.

95
00:12:13,563 --> 00:12:17,807
[SPEAKER_06]: Number four, become a racial equity broker.

96
00:12:19,188 --> 00:12:26,255
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis is the personification of transitioning from a political activist to a politician.

97
00:12:28,942 --> 00:12:35,326
[SPEAKER_06]: I frame it as transitioning from a racial equity advocate to a racial equity broker.

98
00:12:36,907 --> 00:12:46,832
[SPEAKER_06]: A racial equity advocate speaks up and speaks out, stands in the gap and sits at the table to advocate for people who cannot advocate for themselves.

99
00:12:50,174 --> 00:12:56,458
[SPEAKER_06]: There is a saying, if you are not at the table, you are on the menu and someone is eating you for lunch.

100
00:12:59,537 --> 00:13:05,963
[SPEAKER_06]: Shirley Chisholm said, if they don't give you a seat at the table, bring a folding chair.

101
00:13:10,146 --> 00:13:15,671
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis realized that to make transformative change, he had to be at the table and often bring his own chair.

102
00:13:16,572 --> 00:13:21,857
[SPEAKER_06]: Once at the table, he realized that he needed to help draft the documents that got discussed at the table.

103
00:13:23,166 --> 00:13:36,829
[SPEAKER_06]: This led him to becoming an elected official and a racial equity broker to alter, deconstruct, and restructure the laws, policies, and procedures, and the rules that inhibit racial equity.

104
00:13:37,869 --> 00:13:42,590
[SPEAKER_06]: And last but not least, number five, never give up.

105
00:13:45,130 --> 00:13:47,511
[SPEAKER_06]: When Lewis was elected to Congress in 1986,

106
00:13:51,272 --> 00:13:58,417
[SPEAKER_06]: One of his first bills was the creation of a national museum to chronicle the history and culture and successes of black Americans.

107
00:13:59,938 --> 00:14:08,183
[SPEAKER_06]: The culmination of this bill was passed in 2003 and opened in 2016 as the National Museum of African American History and Culture.

108
00:14:15,117 --> 00:14:17,299
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis taught us persistence.

109
00:14:18,159 --> 00:14:23,863
[SPEAKER_06]: He taught us that when a person has transformative ideas, they should not taper those ideas.

110
00:14:25,004 --> 00:14:29,247
[SPEAKER_06]: Instead, they should push those ideas until others get on board.

111
00:14:31,048 --> 00:14:38,633
[SPEAKER_06]: Simply because change is slow does not mean change agents have to move slowly towards it.

112
00:14:40,375 --> 00:14:46,642
[SPEAKER_06]: Lewis was a lightning bolt for equity, social justice, and social change.

113
00:14:47,623 --> 00:14:56,313
[SPEAKER_06]: We must continue his legacy and never forget history, always pursue equity, and let's get in some good trouble.

114
00:14:57,814 --> 00:14:58,155
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

115
00:15:59,080 --> 00:16:03,122
[SPEAKER_11]: I just, just wow, just wow.

116
00:16:03,142 --> 00:16:11,064
[SPEAKER_11]: So thank you all three, my dear friends, Beth and Stacy and Bobby, Robert Hayes.

117
00:16:16,288 --> 00:16:21,514
[SPEAKER_11]: I stand with you in believing that all three civil rights champions changed the world for the good.

118
00:16:22,175 --> 00:16:25,799
[SPEAKER_11]: Their sacrifices are both historic and well-documented.

119
00:16:26,319 --> 00:16:32,526
[SPEAKER_11]: Sharing these reflections gives the opportunity to see Martin Luther King Jr.'

120
00:16:32,506 --> 00:16:36,170
[SPEAKER_11]: 's collaborative influence over so many in the movement.

121
00:16:38,258 --> 00:16:45,100
[SPEAKER_11]: As we move forward, I want us to move even more deeply into today's theme and challenge.

122
00:16:45,700 --> 00:16:54,563
[SPEAKER_11]: So if you don't mind indulging the poet in me, I'd like to share a new piece written for just such a time as this.

123
00:16:55,523 --> 00:16:59,945
[SPEAKER_11]: It's my first time sharing it, and I hope it gets you fired up.

124
00:17:00,965 --> 00:17:07,307
[SPEAKER_11]: Please give this rendition a mindful listen if we don't quit.

125
00:17:09,273 --> 00:17:17,616
[SPEAKER_11]: If we don't quit, we can protest our plight with the alacrity and tenacity of Medgar and Malcolm and Martin.

126
00:17:18,497 --> 00:17:25,199
[SPEAKER_11]: We can purge our psyches of guilt and shame and isolation like Mandela at Robin Island's release.

127
00:17:26,180 --> 00:17:30,622
[SPEAKER_11]: We can pause the clock on the desecration of our tribes and our villages.

128
00:17:30,702 --> 00:17:36,204
[SPEAKER_11]: We can plow the fields of our ancestors and plant the seeds of the dreams they left us.

129
00:17:37,354 --> 00:17:43,719
[SPEAKER_11]: We can post the news of the fall of our demons and pursue new justice with grace and creativity.

130
00:17:43,779 --> 00:17:51,345
[SPEAKER_11]: We can push back against the ugliness and ignorance of a society drunk again with predatory whiteness.

131
00:17:52,359 --> 00:17:59,167
[SPEAKER_11]: We can plan celebrations with our true allies and propose toasts and salute our heroes.

132
00:17:59,867 --> 00:18:04,012
[SPEAKER_11]: We can promote our culture with righteous pride in the face of our detractors.

133
00:18:04,373 --> 00:18:10,379
[SPEAKER_11]: We can protect our progeny, our probity, and our dignity with the content of our character.

134
00:18:11,160 --> 00:18:17,967
[SPEAKER_11]: We can peacefully advance against red lines and black codes and institutional systems of oppression.

135
00:18:18,367 --> 00:18:22,451
[SPEAKER_11]: We can purposefully move the wheels of positive change forward.

136
00:18:22,492 --> 00:18:27,657
[SPEAKER_11]: We can permanently say no to hate for hate's sake alone.

137
00:18:29,038 --> 00:18:30,239
[SPEAKER_11]: If we don't quit.

138
00:18:31,208 --> 00:18:35,752
[SPEAKER_11]: We will vindicate the sacrifices of our lost leaders and slain advocates.

139
00:18:36,353 --> 00:18:41,458
[SPEAKER_11]: We will validate the legitimacy of our journey to diversity, equity, and inclusion.

140
00:18:41,518 --> 00:18:47,123
[SPEAKER_11]: We will venerate the greatness of our poets, prophets, griots, and sages.

141
00:18:47,463 --> 00:18:56,352
[SPEAKER_11]: We will rightly divide the testimonies of our seers and record the witness like Ida B., Zora Neale, Maya, and Nikki.

142
00:18:57,179 --> 00:19:01,200
[SPEAKER_11]: We will vacuum up the dirt that a mountain of malice has heaped upon us.

143
00:19:01,280 --> 00:19:09,363
[SPEAKER_11]: We will vouchsafe an inheritance of restoration and repair for a sea of iniquities against us.

144
00:19:10,163 --> 00:19:15,645
[SPEAKER_11]: We will vaporize a legion of assassins who lie in wait for any lack of vigilance.

145
00:19:16,345 --> 00:19:23,228
[SPEAKER_11]: We will visualize with eyes wide open the hazardous ascent of the hellbound and the hysterical.

146
00:19:24,247 --> 00:19:29,915
[SPEAKER_11]: We will vaccinate our young with the overflowing vial of courage under fire.

147
00:19:31,242 --> 00:19:32,502
[SPEAKER_11]: if we don't quit.

148
00:19:33,343 --> 00:19:40,905
[SPEAKER_11]: New histories will avow that we were as valorous as Nat Turner and Denmark Vesey and Sister Rosa.

149
00:19:41,485 --> 00:19:49,027
[SPEAKER_11]: That we rose victorious like Monsa Musa, Shaka Zulu, and the Black Moors who civilized Aryan heathens across Europe.

150
00:19:49,708 --> 00:19:57,230
[SPEAKER_11]: That we called out vociferously to mass denizens who perched in the caverns and bivouacs, come out if you dare.

151
00:19:58,354 --> 00:20:08,980
[SPEAKER_11]: that we form the vanguard who watches over the village in silent strength, that we rent asunder the veils, cloaks, and robes of the angry mobs and frenzied marauders.

152
00:20:09,981 --> 00:20:15,744
[SPEAKER_11]: If we don't quit, we can cast our vote for brown equity and black excellence.

153
00:20:16,284 --> 00:20:22,588
[SPEAKER_11]: We can assemble in new vicinities and new vacancies and new versions of our former vagrancy.

154
00:20:23,593 --> 00:20:29,458
[SPEAKER_11]: We can add glowingly to the lyricist's verses and the composer's canon and the arranger's concerto.

155
00:20:30,098 --> 00:20:35,743
[SPEAKER_11]: We can bring harmony and melody to the mix of global voices who make up our choir.

156
00:20:36,363 --> 00:20:42,228
[SPEAKER_11]: We can pen indelible pages, chapters, and volumes to the stories of a thousand nations.

157
00:20:42,648 --> 00:20:50,755
[SPEAKER_11]: We can be deemed so valiant that the slings and arrows of the bard's decree will cease to call our fortune outrageous.

158
00:20:51,645 --> 00:21:00,528
[SPEAKER_11]: We can regard the night sky with blissful wonder while inquisitors sleep forever in the hard bed of their own fiery damnation.

159
00:21:01,248 --> 00:21:11,072
[SPEAKER_11]: We can be resolute in knowing that their litany of vice will never cradle their heads with aught but recrimination and regrets.

160
00:21:12,372 --> 00:21:13,753
[SPEAKER_11]: If we don't quit,

161
00:21:14,663 --> 00:21:16,925
[SPEAKER_11]: We will give the valedictory address.

162
00:21:17,665 --> 00:21:21,288
[SPEAKER_11]: We will speak of veracity and visions and vanity fair.

163
00:21:21,708 --> 00:21:25,251
[SPEAKER_11]: We will curse visions, vituperation, and vile intent.

164
00:21:25,771 --> 00:21:31,656
[SPEAKER_11]: We will castigate the pervasive virus of racism and social justice in our midst.

165
00:21:32,537 --> 00:21:34,778
[SPEAKER_11]: We will lead the songs of our people.

166
00:21:35,359 --> 00:21:37,921
[SPEAKER_11]: This land is your land.

167
00:21:38,541 --> 00:21:40,783
[SPEAKER_11]: This land is my land.

168
00:21:41,523 --> 00:21:43,465
[SPEAKER_11]: This land was made for you and me.

169
00:21:44,795 --> 00:21:50,518
[SPEAKER_11]: For deep in my heart, I do believe we shall overcome someday.

170
00:21:51,699 --> 00:22:02,384
[SPEAKER_11]: And free at last, free at last, thank God almighty, we are free at last.

171
00:22:11,830 --> 00:22:12,330
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

172
00:22:12,350 --> 00:22:12,390
[SPEAKER_11]: OK.

173
00:22:15,987 --> 00:22:16,207
[SPEAKER_11]: So.

174
00:22:19,128 --> 00:22:19,569
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

175
00:22:19,689 --> 00:22:20,089
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

176
00:22:21,649 --> 00:22:21,870
[SPEAKER_11]: So.

177
00:22:25,051 --> 00:22:25,311
[SPEAKER_11]: We.

178
00:22:28,772 --> 00:22:29,733
[SPEAKER_11]: OK, let me do it like this.

179
00:22:30,553 --> 00:22:32,534
[SPEAKER_11]: Are you engaged to move forward with us?

180
00:22:33,895 --> 00:22:34,675
