01:42:20,296 --> 01:42:21,258
[SPEAKER_00]: Good afternoon.

660
01:42:21,278 --> 01:42:34,398
[SPEAKER_00]: I was saying to Robert, so I've been in and out of this area for about 20 years, and this is by far the kindest place I have been in all those 20 years, so just thank you for welcoming me.

661
01:42:37,668 --> 01:42:44,937
[SPEAKER_00]: And thank you to Terry and his wife, Teresa, for inviting me to be here with you for this Martin Luther King Day celebration.

662
01:42:45,398 --> 01:42:49,323
[SPEAKER_00]: I also want to thank the Tufts University Office of Government and Community Relations.

663
01:42:49,763 --> 01:42:55,330
[SPEAKER_00]: It really is a pleasure to be with you all, to be in this space, and to be in community.

664
01:42:56,211 --> 01:43:01,454
[SPEAKER_00]: As you heard from Terry, my name is Dr. Sarah Bleich, and I have a couple of different hats.

665
01:43:02,074 --> 01:43:07,176
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm on the faculty at the School of Public Health at Harvard in the Kennedy School and still do academic research.

666
01:43:07,596 --> 01:43:14,700
[SPEAKER_00]: And I also have this Administrator hat where I am a vice provost and lead our Legacy of Slavery initiative.

667
01:43:15,540 --> 01:43:33,651
[SPEAKER_00]: And in our time today, I want to reflect on the words and wisdom of Dr. Martin Luther King, to share some of the work that we are doing at Harvard, and most importantly, to connect on the theme of this year's celebration, if we don't quit.

668
01:43:34,796 --> 01:43:43,579
[SPEAKER_00]: But before I do that, I wanna begin by acknowledging several individuals whose lives, labor, and leadership anchor us today.

669
01:43:44,859 --> 01:43:53,222
[SPEAKER_00]: So earlier, about an hour ago, we posthumously honored Mr. Clarence Ed Ligon for civic engagement.

670
01:43:53,702 --> 01:43:59,644
[SPEAKER_00]: We also honored Miss Adele Chavezano for her commitment and impact to arts and culture.

671
01:44:00,570 --> 01:44:00,770
[SPEAKER_00]: Ms.

672
01:44:00,810 --> 01:44:05,013
[SPEAKER_00]: Stacey Clayton for her faith in action, and Ms.

673
01:44:05,053 --> 01:44:07,976
[SPEAKER_00]: Gwendolyn Lee for her enduring legacy.

674
01:44:08,996 --> 01:44:10,097
[SPEAKER_00]: Mr. Ligon, Ms.

675
01:44:10,137 --> 01:44:11,558
[SPEAKER_00]: Travisano, Ms.

676
01:44:11,598 --> 01:44:12,399
[SPEAKER_00]: Clayton, and Ms.

677
01:44:12,499 --> 01:44:30,112
[SPEAKER_00]: Lee, we thank you all again because Medford wouldn't be what it is today without your tireless dedication and commitment to preserving the history of this city and working together to ensure that it remains strong, daring not to quit.

678
01:44:30,512 --> 01:44:32,617
[SPEAKER_00]: Please join me once again in congratulating them.

679
01:44:41,445 --> 01:44:54,533
[SPEAKER_00]: I would also like to reflect back and to acknowledge someone who lived and labored in this very city hundreds of years ago, not even a mile from where we're sitting right now, Miss Belinda Sutton.

680
01:44:55,614 --> 01:45:00,677
[SPEAKER_00]: Miss Belinda Sutton was an African woman enslaved at the royal house in Medford.

681
01:45:01,718 --> 01:45:05,901
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, me and my team went and visited the Royal House around this time last year.

682
01:45:06,261 --> 01:45:12,064
[SPEAKER_00]: It was winter moving into spring, and two things stood out to me on that visit.

683
01:45:13,025 --> 01:45:28,074
[SPEAKER_00]: One was when we were upstairs in the bedrooms, one of the things that Dr. Keira Singleton, who's the executive director, explained to us is that enslaved women would sleep on the feet of their enslavers to keep them warm.

684
01:45:29,347 --> 01:45:31,028
[SPEAKER_00]: And it was a really cold day that day.

685
01:45:31,888 --> 01:45:42,374
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'm fully dressed, my feet are kind of cold, and I'm imagining sleeping on the feet of someone else to keep their feet warm while my feet are freezing.

686
01:45:43,815 --> 01:45:49,458
[SPEAKER_00]: The second thing that really stuck with me on that visit was going downstairs into the kitchen area.

687
01:45:50,379 --> 01:45:54,621
[SPEAKER_00]: And there was this very fancy equivalent of a spit for making meat.

688
01:45:55,902 --> 01:46:11,581
[SPEAKER_00]: And she explained that the reason that the house had made this really big investment in this spit was because the number one cause of death for women was being burned to death by their undergarments and their clothes being set on fire from the flame.

689
01:46:12,802 --> 01:46:17,944
[SPEAKER_00]: But the purpose of that spit was not to protect and care for the enslaved.

690
01:46:18,825 --> 01:46:24,107
[SPEAKER_00]: The purpose of that spit was to make sure that the property of the enslavers didn't die.

691
01:46:25,147 --> 01:46:36,532
[SPEAKER_00]: And I just think about those moments, and it's just, it's amazing the history of this country, and bless you, and the Royal House and Slave Quarters literally is not even a mile away from here.

692
01:46:38,233 --> 01:46:38,633
[SPEAKER_00]: So Ms.

693
01:46:38,653 --> 01:46:47,358
[SPEAKER_00]: Sutton survived the Middle Passage, years of forced labor at the royal estate, the abandonment of her enslaver during the American Revolution.

694
01:46:47,838 --> 01:46:51,760
[SPEAKER_00]: And in 1783, she did something extraordinary.

695
01:46:52,481 --> 01:47:00,025
[SPEAKER_00]: She petitioned the Massachusetts legislature for a pension from the estate that had profited from her enslavement.

696
01:47:00,665 --> 01:47:04,728
[SPEAKER_00]: Her petition was approved, and one payment was made.

697
01:47:05,628 --> 01:47:12,033
[SPEAKER_00]: But then she had many, many efforts to request the rest of the money she was owed and was unsuccessful.

698
01:47:12,573 --> 01:47:13,073
[SPEAKER_00]: But Ms.

699
01:47:13,274 --> 01:47:15,915
[SPEAKER_00]: Sutton never stopped trying.

700
01:47:16,716 --> 01:47:26,283
[SPEAKER_00]: This is one of the earliest documented accounts of an African woman in America plagued by slavery's chains, daring not to quit.

701
01:47:27,481 --> 01:47:42,152
[SPEAKER_00]: And of course, we honor the reason that we are all here today, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., a man who held many titles for those that were close to him, a son, a husband, a father, a friend, a minister.

702
01:47:42,792 --> 01:47:48,276
[SPEAKER_00]: For the rest of us, he was the leader of the Civil Rights Movement, beginning when he was just in his 20s.

703
01:47:49,895 --> 01:48:04,932
[SPEAKER_00]: Dr. King followed his grandfather and his father's footsteps, became a pastor, and preached his first sermon as a teenager in Ebenezer Baptist Church, nurturing his gift of moving and inspiring millions through public speaking.

704
01:48:06,093 --> 01:48:18,576
[SPEAKER_00]: Dr. King was a man who saw what the future could be if people came together and stood up for what is right, for what is just, and what is true, daring not to quit.

705
01:48:19,656 --> 01:48:25,438
[SPEAKER_00]: Today's theme, If We Don't Quit, could be the subtitle of Dr. King's legacy.

706
01:48:26,338 --> 01:48:35,300
[SPEAKER_00]: In a powerful speech at Spelman College in 1960, he said, and this is on the crossword search that we just did, if you can't fly,

707
01:48:36,000 --> 01:48:36,500
[SPEAKER_00]: then run.

708
01:48:37,361 --> 01:48:39,742
[SPEAKER_00]: If you can't run, then walk.

709
01:48:40,482 --> 01:48:43,543
[SPEAKER_00]: And if you can't walk, then crawl.

710
01:48:44,083 --> 01:48:48,385
[SPEAKER_00]: But whatever you do, you have to keep moving forward.

711
01:48:49,146 --> 01:48:52,007
[SPEAKER_00]: And move forward we must and we will.

712
01:48:52,987 --> 01:48:59,029
[SPEAKER_00]: Dr. King's words are a powerful reminder of the importance of perseverance for progress.

713
01:48:59,529 --> 01:49:02,909
[SPEAKER_00]: And they are not just something that makes us feel inspired today.

714
01:49:03,330 --> 01:49:13,132
[SPEAKER_00]: They are a strategy for tomorrow and something that I hold as I move forward in the implementation work around Harvard's Legacy of Slavery initiative.

715
01:49:13,932 --> 01:49:18,076
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, I come at the legacy of slavery work with a public health lens.

716
01:49:18,536 --> 01:49:29,046
[SPEAKER_00]: For the past two decades, I have dedicated my career to building evidence for policies to help communities live longer, healthier lives through academic research and translation.

717
01:49:29,066 --> 01:49:38,095
[SPEAKER_00]: I've also, as you heard from Terry, had the opportunity to serve twice in the federal government, first under the Obama administration and then in the Biden administration.

718
01:49:39,355 --> 01:49:43,977
[SPEAKER_00]: But my commitment to historically underserved communities is deeply personal.

719
01:49:44,617 --> 01:49:56,801
[SPEAKER_00]: So I grew up in inner city Baltimore, and I was just telling Robert before we started that walking into this room is the first time I have felt like I am in Baltimore in Boston.

720
01:49:57,241 --> 01:50:01,803
[SPEAKER_00]: And that is because of the kindness of this room, and you really are to be commended for that.

721
01:50:07,807 --> 01:50:16,249
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, growing up, I had my parents, and then I have a twin sister, who is my heart, and an older brother, and my parents were both public school teachers.

722
01:50:16,489 --> 01:50:19,290
[SPEAKER_00]: And my mom did special ed, my dad did high school English.

723
01:50:19,690 --> 01:50:24,972
[SPEAKER_00]: I can't go anywhere to this day in Baltimore with my father without someone saying, Mr. Bleich, Mr. Bleich.

724
01:50:25,012 --> 01:50:25,892
[SPEAKER_00]: He knows everybody.

725
01:50:26,412 --> 01:50:32,154
[SPEAKER_00]: The other thing he did is that for the last part of his teaching career, he taught English

726
01:50:33,014 --> 01:50:36,918
[SPEAKER_00]: at an engineering high school, the top engineering high school in the city.

727
01:50:37,398 --> 01:50:39,881
[SPEAKER_00]: So you had to get through my dad to graduate.

728
01:50:40,241 --> 01:50:47,608
[SPEAKER_00]: And so there is a lot of folklore about these engineering students learning how to write well because my dad insisted on excellence in writing.

729
01:50:49,131 --> 01:50:59,378
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, because my parents were public school teachers and because my mom stepped back from the workforce when we were young, my family received SNAP, which you may know as food stamps.

730
01:51:00,018 --> 01:51:01,619
[SPEAKER_00]: My family received WIC.

731
01:51:02,120 --> 01:51:04,481
[SPEAKER_00]: And me and my siblings, we received school meals.

732
01:51:05,062 --> 01:51:09,105
[SPEAKER_00]: So I know firsthand the difference that those programs can make.

733
01:51:09,325 --> 01:51:18,471
[SPEAKER_00]: So it has been a pleasure and honor of my career to be able to explore how do you strengthen the public health impacts of federal nutrition assistance programs.

734
01:51:19,071 --> 01:51:27,995
[SPEAKER_00]: And because I know how powerful these programs are, personally and professionally, this current moment that we are in is especially painful.

735
01:51:28,736 --> 01:51:35,819
[SPEAKER_00]: As many of you know, federal nutrition policy has undergone some of the steepest rollbacks in decades.

736
01:51:36,419 --> 01:51:42,542
[SPEAKER_00]: So last year, 2025, the One Big Beautiful Bill Act, or HR1, was passed.

737
01:51:43,262 --> 01:51:52,014
[SPEAKER_00]: It does many things, including reduces federal spending on SNAP by $186 billion.

738
01:51:53,155 --> 01:51:57,401
[SPEAKER_00]: That is the steepest cut in the history of the program, and it's about 20%.

739
01:51:59,343 --> 01:52:05,488
[SPEAKER_00]: That means that millions and millions of people are not going to be able to participate in that program.

740
01:52:06,489 --> 01:52:13,174
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, these harms are going to be compounded by the cuts through the One Big Beautiful Bill Act to Medicaid.

741
01:52:13,814 --> 01:52:19,679
[SPEAKER_00]: A trillion dollars over 10 years means 10 million people are going to lose benefits.

742
01:52:20,399 --> 01:52:24,683
[SPEAKER_00]: Many people who participate in Medicaid also participate in SNAP.

743
01:52:25,324 --> 01:52:28,407
[SPEAKER_00]: So families are facing collateral impacts.

744
01:52:29,047 --> 01:52:36,694
[SPEAKER_00]: These are likely friends, family, people that you know well, but these changes are going to affect real people in real ways.

745
01:52:37,075 --> 01:52:40,978
[SPEAKER_00]: And in moments like these, it can be hard to know where to lean in.

746
01:52:41,919 --> 01:52:48,847
[SPEAKER_00]: And when I feel that way, I return to my North Star, helping underserved communities achieve a better quality of life.

747
01:52:49,327 --> 01:52:54,994
[SPEAKER_00]: And in this season of change, that is my way of daring not to quit.

748
01:52:56,175 --> 01:53:03,303
[SPEAKER_00]: Now, my work in public health was a launchpad for doing the implementation work for Harvard Legacy of Slavery Initiative.

749
01:53:04,229 --> 01:53:08,692
[SPEAKER_00]: But there's also a very personal moment that primed me for this position.

750
01:53:09,413 --> 01:53:18,599
[SPEAKER_00]: So in 2017, on this day, on MLK, MLK celebration, I was at the JFK Library with my girls.

751
01:53:19,060 --> 01:53:22,382
[SPEAKER_00]: They were then four and six or five and seven.

752
01:53:23,463 --> 01:53:28,186
[SPEAKER_00]: And the focus of that day was the soundtrack to MLK's life.

753
01:53:29,287 --> 01:53:34,791
[SPEAKER_00]: So the MC is describing one of the songs, it was a spiritual, and he mentions slavery.

754
01:53:35,792 --> 01:53:41,576
[SPEAKER_00]: My then seven-year-old child, my oldest, turns to me and says, Mama, what's slavery?

755
01:53:42,297 --> 01:53:49,042
[SPEAKER_00]: Now before I tell you what I said, I come from a family where manners and kindness are everything.

756
01:53:49,582 --> 01:53:54,625
[SPEAKER_00]: So if you're inconsiderate, if you are mean to someone else, you will get in a world of trouble.

757
01:53:55,266 --> 01:54:04,092
[SPEAKER_00]: It is a value that my parents have loudly instilled in myself and my siblings and to my children and one that I really try to reinforce.

758
01:54:05,390 --> 01:54:09,072
[SPEAKER_00]: So I turn to my seven-year-old who says to me, Mama, what's slavery?

759
01:54:09,092 --> 01:54:13,355
[SPEAKER_00]: And I explain it using seven-year-old terminology.

760
01:54:13,415 --> 01:54:14,896
[SPEAKER_00]: She might have been six, I can't remember.

761
01:54:14,916 --> 01:54:19,399
[SPEAKER_00]: And I just, I watch, literally watch the wheels turning in her head.

762
01:54:19,419 --> 01:54:23,562
[SPEAKER_00]: And she looks at me and she said, Mama, that was rude.

763
01:54:24,968 --> 01:54:26,308
[SPEAKER_00]: And I said, you know what, honey?

764
01:54:26,548 --> 01:54:28,129
[SPEAKER_00]: It was extremely rude.

765
01:54:28,589 --> 01:54:31,149
[SPEAKER_00]: And for her, that was like a four-letter word.

766
01:54:31,730 --> 01:54:35,550
[SPEAKER_00]: Because again, we were told you can't be inconsiderate, you can't be rude.

767
01:54:36,271 --> 01:54:39,371
[SPEAKER_00]: And so I often think about that conversation.

768
01:54:40,031 --> 01:54:45,333
[SPEAKER_00]: She had such moral clarity so quickly about what slavery was.

769
01:54:46,073 --> 01:54:51,334
[SPEAKER_00]: It was profoundly wrong, and it was deeply disrespectful to human dignity.

770
01:54:52,705 --> 01:55:07,017
[SPEAKER_00]: So in 2022, Harvard released a report detailing the university's direct financial and intellectual ties to slavery, along with seven recommendations for how to advance reparative efforts related to that history.

771
01:55:07,897 --> 01:55:11,140
[SPEAKER_00]: And the report taught us three difficult truths.

772
01:55:11,560 --> 01:55:15,403
[SPEAKER_00]: The first, Harvard has direct ties to slavery.

773
01:55:15,824 --> 01:55:21,608
[SPEAKER_00]: Harvard leaders, Harvard faculty, Harvard staff, enslaved people in Massachusetts and beyond.

774
01:55:22,549 --> 01:55:24,950
[SPEAKER_00]: Harvard has financial ties to slavery.

775
01:55:25,551 --> 01:55:30,694
[SPEAKER_00]: The university benefited from donors and investments rooted in the slave economy.

776
01:55:31,394 --> 01:55:35,196
[SPEAKER_00]: And the third is that Harvard has intellectual ties to slavery.

777
01:55:35,576 --> 01:55:41,880
[SPEAKER_00]: Harvard scholars helped build and legitimize the racist ideas that justified slavery and segregation.

778
01:55:42,620 --> 01:55:50,222
[SPEAKER_00]: If you're interested to read the report, I've brought a bunch of copies with me that you're welcome to take, and it's also freely available online if you want to learn more.

779
01:55:51,162 --> 01:55:54,463
[SPEAKER_00]: One important thing to know is that the report was voluntary.

780
01:55:55,043 --> 01:56:04,185
[SPEAKER_00]: No one forced Harvard to look in the mirror, but as Dr. King taught us, the time is always right to do what is right.

781
01:56:05,225 --> 01:56:08,126
[SPEAKER_00]: The university is nearly 400 years old.

782
01:56:08,626 --> 01:56:12,307
[SPEAKER_00]: It was past time to be honest about its history.

783
01:56:13,448 --> 01:56:28,218
[SPEAKER_00]: In response, Harvard created the Legacy of Slavery Initiative with a $100 million endowment to cast light on the university's legacies of slavery and address the enduring consequences of slavery through purposeful change.

784
01:56:28,618 --> 01:56:30,460
[SPEAKER_00]: And I was asked to lead this work in 2023.

785
01:56:32,441 --> 01:56:35,743
[SPEAKER_00]: At the initiative, we have three main priorities.

786
01:56:36,323 --> 01:56:44,527
[SPEAKER_00]: One is memorializing those who were enslaved by Harvard affiliates while educating the community on the university's ties to slavery.

787
01:56:45,187 --> 01:56:50,030
[SPEAKER_00]: Another is strengthening partnerships with historically black colleges and universities, or HBCUs.

788
01:56:50,650 --> 01:56:55,933
[SPEAKER_00]: And the third is identifying direct descendants of those enslaved by Harvard affiliates.

789
01:56:56,653 --> 01:57:16,017
[SPEAKER_00]: To me, the work that we are doing today is a way to honor Dr. King's legacy and many other leaders like him, like many of you in this room, who have dedicated your lives to addressing legacies of slavery and their impact on communities, never giving up and daring not to quit.

790
01:57:17,554 --> 01:57:24,680
[SPEAKER_00]: In 1962, Dr. King came to Harvard Law School, and he gave a talk, and it was called The Future of Integration.

791
01:57:25,621 --> 01:57:30,765
[SPEAKER_00]: He told the audience that to have an integrated society, we can do one of three things.

792
01:57:31,665 --> 01:57:45,336
[SPEAKER_00]: We can observe the state of our world today and live in extreme optimism, which calls us to do nothing, always thinking the best while ignoring some painful realities of what's going on around us.

793
01:57:46,397 --> 01:57:59,906
[SPEAKER_00]: Or, we can observe the state of our world today and live in extreme pessimism, which calls on us to digress, see all the problems, create more problems, while solving zero problems.

794
01:58:01,369 --> 01:58:17,738
[SPEAKER_00]: or we can observe the state of our world today and combine the truths of extreme optimism and extreme pessimism and be thankful for how far we have come while understanding that we have a long way to go.

795
01:58:18,578 --> 01:58:30,345
[SPEAKER_00]: And here we are, 64 years later, living in a reality that reflects much of the sociopolitical environment during Dr. King's time while also demonstrating progress

796
01:58:31,385 --> 01:58:32,848
[SPEAKER_00]: Yet, we have a long way to go.

797
01:58:32,868 --> 01:58:38,639
[SPEAKER_00]: And we can only get there together if we dare not to quit.

798
01:58:39,930 --> 01:58:46,555
[SPEAKER_00]: At Harvard, we're not quitting and remain committed to the implementation work at the Harvard Legacy of Slavery Initiative.

799
01:58:47,056 --> 01:59:02,928
[SPEAKER_00]: Some of the ways we live out this commitment are providing individuals and groups with an introduction to what slavery looked like in the 17th, 18th, and 19th century New England, and how Harvard played a major role in it through our guided and self-guided tour experiences.

800
01:59:03,348 --> 01:59:06,670
[SPEAKER_00]: We would love to welcome you all on a guided tour this spring.

801
01:59:06,770 --> 01:59:08,631
[SPEAKER_00]: Feel free to reach out and we can set that up.

802
01:59:09,031 --> 01:59:13,654
[SPEAKER_00]: Or the self-guided option is always available and you can take it at any time that's convenient for you.

803
01:59:14,414 --> 01:59:24,720
[SPEAKER_00]: Many who participate in these tours are stunned that this history is in our backyard and that slavery wasn't something that only happened in the South.

804
01:59:25,940 --> 01:59:30,982
[SPEAKER_00]: Another way Harvard lives out its commitment is through partnerships with HBCUs.

805
01:59:31,443 --> 01:59:36,305
[SPEAKER_00]: For example, we are currently in the third year of offering a program called the Du Bois Scholars Program.

806
01:59:36,685 --> 01:59:42,347
[SPEAKER_00]: It's a summer research internship for rising juniors and seniors at research-intensive HBCUs.

807
01:59:42,387 --> 01:59:44,548
[SPEAKER_00]: We partner with 21 different institutions.

808
01:59:45,289 --> 01:59:52,632
[SPEAKER_00]: And past participants have impacted Harvard through planting seeds that inspire further research by Harvard faculty members,

809
01:59:53,512 --> 02:00:02,234
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'm proud that Harvard gets to help participants to deepen their research skills and develop a strong network of peers through their involvement with the program.

810
02:00:02,914 --> 02:00:07,395
[SPEAKER_00]: This past fall, I had a focus group with a number of the faculty that participated.

811
02:00:08,296 --> 02:00:22,119
[SPEAKER_00]: And one of them, who's been a faculty member for the past two summers, said that in his 26 years of being on the faculty at Harvard Medical School, being a mentor in this program is the most rewarding thing that he's done.

812
02:00:23,479 --> 02:00:36,566
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think we at Harvard are so privileged to have these amazing fellows from HBCUs come with their confidence, with their brilliance, with their energy, with their excitement, and honestly make Harvard a better place.

813
02:00:37,186 --> 02:00:40,368
[SPEAKER_00]: So this is a space where we're probably gaining more than we're giving.

814
02:00:41,428 --> 02:00:47,813
[SPEAKER_00]: The last example I'll leave you with is that we're currently working alongside an organization called American Ancestors.

815
02:00:48,233 --> 02:01:00,523
[SPEAKER_00]: They are the oldest genealogical organization in the country, and we're working with them to identify Harvard leaders, Harvard faculty and staff who enslaved people, and the descendants of those who were enslaved.

816
02:01:01,263 --> 02:01:06,848
[SPEAKER_00]: Although it will take multiple years to complete, this work is vital and Harvard remains committed.

817
02:01:07,348 --> 02:01:16,776
[SPEAKER_00]: And if you want to learn more about the implementation work, I've brought along some one-pagers which describe it and there are QR codes in there that you can scan to learn about things in more detail.

818
02:01:18,410 --> 02:01:34,917
[SPEAKER_00]: During times when this work and the values that it represents are being questioned, Dr. King's legacy continually inspires me to keep leading my team to take concrete steps toward Harvard reckoning with the enduring consequences of slavery.

819
02:01:35,697 --> 02:01:43,460
[SPEAKER_00]: The work that we do has real impact on real lives, and we can only do it in community with others.

820
02:01:44,920 --> 02:01:51,065
[SPEAKER_00]: If we don't quit on amplifying history, even when that history is painful.

821
02:01:52,106 --> 02:02:00,493
[SPEAKER_00]: If we don't quit on investing in our communities through civic engagement, arts and culture, faith in action, and legacy building.

822
02:02:01,413 --> 02:02:15,536
[SPEAKER_00]: If we don't quit on building institutions that are accountable, not just prestigious, if we don't quit on each other across every line of difference, then the work of Ms.

823
02:02:15,616 --> 02:02:28,258
[SPEAKER_00]: Belinda Sutton with her petition, the work Dr. King carried through the Civil Rights Movement, and the work that all of you are doing here in Medford will continue to move us towards a more just society.

824
02:02:29,479 --> 02:02:39,190
[SPEAKER_00]: And even when it feels like we're swimming upstream, which is how this moment feels to me, we will make progress and eventually draw closer to the promised land.

825
02:02:39,971 --> 02:02:41,873
[SPEAKER_00]: We cannot quit.

826
02:02:43,134 --> 02:02:45,237
[SPEAKER_00]: Let me close with a simple invitation.

827
02:02:46,758 --> 02:02:54,004
[SPEAKER_00]: Dare not to quit on yourself, on what you built, on what your community built, or on one another.

828
02:02:54,805 --> 02:03:04,253
[SPEAKER_00]: We need each other to build a brighter future in which generations can thrive and in turn help light the way for those who follow.

829
02:03:05,234 --> 02:03:06,775
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you for having me in your space.

830
02:03:29,934 --> 02:03:38,458
[SPEAKER_11]: So I'm smiling from ear to ear, because as you probably do, I love it when a plan comes together.

831
02:03:40,059 --> 02:03:40,939
[SPEAKER_11]: What I heard then.

832
02:03:43,250 --> 02:03:47,711
[SPEAKER_11]: is equivalent in so many ways to what I heard today.

833
02:03:49,211 --> 02:03:51,792
[SPEAKER_11]: Sarah, that was absolutely amazing.

834
02:03:52,552 --> 02:03:58,773
[SPEAKER_11]: And you crystallized everything that we wanted to bring to our audience today.

835
02:03:59,593 --> 02:04:07,535
[SPEAKER_11]: And I want you all to give yourselves a round of applause, because you've been a great audience in braving the elements to join us today.

836
02:04:14,743 --> 02:04:28,707
[SPEAKER_11]: So as we move closer to the close of our program, I would be remiss in this gathering, and I don't think it would be complete if we didn't link arms and sing together.

837
02:04:28,767 --> 02:04:35,189
[SPEAKER_11]: Martin Luther King was a great lover of the gospel, but also of gospel music.

838
02:04:35,709 --> 02:04:44,252
[SPEAKER_11]: And here to present us in another of Dr. King's favorite spirituals, We Shall Overcome, is once again the wonderful Athene Wilson.

839
02:04:53,737 --> 02:05:01,820
[SPEAKER_13]: All right, so if we can stand and make this declaration with music as we sing We Shall Overcome.

840
